Members of the Welsh Assembly do not want to “look like the Muppets”
Among some members of the National Assembly, there is growing discontent with the proposal to adopt the abbreviation MWP (from the English Member of the Welsh Parliament - Member of the Parliament of Wales) for their name.
The problematic decision is related to plans to change the name of the Assembly to the Parliament of Wales.
Members of the Assembly from different political parties are concerned about possible jokes with this abbreviation.
One Labour member, expressing his party's opinion, expressed concern that the new abbreviation "is rhymed with Twp and Pwp".
For our readers, it is not from Wales: in Welsh twp means "stupid", and pwp means "cat".
According to a member of the Assembly from the Party of Wales, his organization as a whole “remained dissatisfied” and offered other options.
Representatives of the conservative party “do not object” to the new abbreviation, but note that MWP is close in spelling to the word Muppet.
In this context, the letter w in Welsh is pronounced roughly like the letter u in Yorkshire English.
The Assembly Committee currently drafting the name change bill issued the following statement: “The final decision on how the Assembly members will be named will, of course, remain with them.”
The Wales Governance Act of 2017 empowers the National Assembly of Wales to change its name.
In June, the Committee published the results of a public opinion poll on the proposed options, according to which the option of “Parliament of Wales” instead of “Assembly” found wide support among the local population.
As for the name of the Assembly members, the Committee expressed its preference for the Welsh Parliament Members (WMP) option, while the MWP option received the greatest public support.
Apparently, members of the Assembly offer other options, but it will not be easy for the presiding member, Elin Jones, to find a solution that suits everyone. Recall that the draft law on changes should be submitted in a few weeks.
Reform laws will include other modifications to the Assembly's working process, including new rules on disqualification of Assembly members and the structure of the Committee's system.
Members of the Assembly will vote on the final version of their name during the debate on the bill.
Macedonians vote in referendum to change their country's name
On Sunday, Macedonians will vote to change the country’s name to the Republic of North Macedonia.
The vote is designed to resolve a decades-old dispute with neighboring Greece, which has its own province of Macedonia.
The Greek government has long insisted that the name "Republic of Macedonia" implies territorial claims to the Greek province, and has repeatedly spoken out against its northern neighbor's accession to the European Union and NATO.
Macedonian President Gheorghe Ivanov, an opponent of the referendum on the name change, said he was not going to recognize its results.
However, supporters of the referendum, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, note that changing the name of the country is just the price of joining the EU and NATO.
