North Korea says it will not unilaterally disarm without trust
North Korea’s foreign minister said at the United Nations on Saturday that the continued sanctions increase mistrust in the United States and that his country would not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under any circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “substantial goodwill measures” last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site, and committing not to build up stockpiles of nuclear weapons or develop nuclear technology.
“However, we do not see a symmetrical reaction from the United States,” he said.
Without trust in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances, we will not be able to unilaterally take the first steps towards disarmament.
While Ri echoed North Korea’s already-sounding complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “step-by-step” approach to denuclearization that would reward North Korea for incremental steps, his statement seemed important in the sense that it did not reject unilateral denuclearization without control, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader, held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim promised to start moving toward “denuclearizing the Korean Peninsula,” and Trump promised North Korea security guarantees.
North Korea seeks to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington also resists calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The U.S. insists that ‘denuclearisation must be done first,’ and raises the level of pressure through sanctions to enforce its goal and even objects to an ‘announcement of an end to the war,’” Ri said.
“The notion that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a utopian dream of people who don’t know us.
But the real problem is that the ongoing sanctions increase our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier in the week.
Instead, the minister focused on three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, and added: “If South Korea, not the United States, were a party to this denuclearization issue, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not be in such a dead end.”
However, the tone of Ri’s speech was sharply different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korea’s missiles on the US mainland was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “suicide missile.”
At the United Nations this year, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said much remained to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea disarms.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not set a timeline for the process: “Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should encourage Pyongyang for the steps that have been taken.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo said at the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The imposition of sanctions by the Security Council must continue actively and mandatory until we see complete, final and confirmed denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions on North Korea since 2006, seeking to cut off funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly summit and said after that meeting that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
