North Korea promised at a meeting held with Moon this month to dismantle the missile complex, as well as the nuclear complex, if the United States, for its part, takes “appropriate measures.”
Kim told him that the “appropriate measures” he was talking about were the security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore, as well as actions aimed at normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students learn to rest on special courses
The new course, introduced this year at Harvard University, has helped all elementary students learn to sleep more and combat the chauvinistic culture of continuous caffeine consumption in order to stay awake all night long.
One academic found that the most successful students in the world often have no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chaisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
After his discovery was made, he became interested in the idea of introducing such a course, having previously made a presentation on the impact of lack of sleep on learning processes.
“At the end of my report, a girl came up to me and said, ‘I’m sorry I only found out about this now that I’m almost finishing my studies.’
She said no one ever told her about the importance of sleep — which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, first offered to students this year, talks about how the habit of healthy sleep contributes to academic and sports performance, as well as how it improves the overall well-being of a person.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University Health Service, says the university decided to introduce this course after it was found that students were experiencing severe sleep deprivation during the school week.
The lesson lasts one hour, students perform a number of interactive tasks.
One section of the class offers an image of a dormitory room where students, by clicking on coffee cups, curtains, exercisers and books, get information about how each of these activities and substances — coffee, light, which cause lack of sleep — affect athletic performance, and how important it is to get enough sleep every day.
In another section, participants learn how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The interactive campus map encourages course participants to reflect on their daily lives.
“We understand that these classes will not change the behavior of students at once.
But we believe they have a right to know how anyone else has a right to know, for example, how smoking affects their health,” added Professor Chaisler.
A false sense of pride that a person can “smell all night” is still fairly common, he said, and modern technology, as well as increasing pressure on students, means sleep deprivation is becoming a problem.
According to him, a sufficient amount of good quality sleep is a “secret weapon” of the student to combat stress, nervous exhaustion and anxiety, and even to combat excess weight, as lack of sleep puts the brain into starvation mode, causing it to constantly feel hungry.
Raymond Soe, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped develop the course by attending one of the classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to spread this information throughout the campus.
He hopes the next step is to ask all graduate students to take a similar curriculum before entering a competitive institution.
Professor Chaisler recommends that students set an alarm clock warning to go to bed and wake up, as well as remember the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lamps, which disrupts a person’s biorhythm and leads to problems with falling asleep.
