The method is to extract immune cells from the patient and change them in the laboratory.
As a result of this change, cells gain the ability to “see” the type of protein that is characteristic of many types of cancer, then the cells must be reintroduced.
The trial vaccine shows promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
In one patient who was injected with this vaccine, and whose immune system has learned to recognize abnormal cells, ovarian cancer has been in remission for more than 18 months.
The method is to extract immune cells from the patient and change them in the laboratory, after which the altered cells can “see” the protein HER2, characteristic of many types of cancer, then the altered cells are re-introduced to the patient.
Professor Jay Berzofsky, of the U.S. National Cancer Research Institute, in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “The results we have obtained hint that we have a very promising vaccine.”
Professor Berzofsky explains: HER2 “stimulates the growth of several types of cancer,” including breast, ovarian, lung, and colorectal cancer.
