The World Citizens Festival, which opened in 2012, is a follow-up to a global anti-poverty project led by an international group of human rights defenders hoping to end poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
To get a free ticket to an event (unless you’re willing to pay for a VIP ticket), you had to volunteer or send an email to a world leader, make a phone call, or take any other or other meaningful action to help raise awareness about your goal of ending poverty.
But how successful has the Festival of World Citizens been in 12 years in terms of achieving its goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people to attend a concert truly convincing fellow citizens to demand a call to action, or is it just another case of so-called “clicktivism” where people believe they are making real changes by signing an online petition or sending messages on Twitter?
Organizers of Global Citizen say that since 2011, the festival has registered more than 19 million “shares” held by its supporters, which pursue many different goals.
It is mentioned that thanks to these actions, world leaders have promised to allocate funds worth more than $ 37 billion, which should affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
