National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
A new study, conducted in one of the Scottish Highlands estates, aims to show how bats use the landscape in search of food.
It is hoped that the data obtained will allow a new look at the behavior of unique winged mammals and will help in further conservation activities of the species.
The study, organized by scientists at the National Endowment for Scotland, will examine common netopyrs, netopyrs sopranos, and brown long-haired bats and night owls Dobanton inhabiting Inverewe Gardens, Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be installed at some points around the site to track the actions of bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile terrain surveys using hand-held detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of screams, as well as the types of activities for which various groups of these animals are responsible.
A habitat map will then be drawn up and a report prepared to create a detailed picture of their landscape-scale behavior.
Rob Dewar, a conservation advisor at NTS, hopes these results will show which habitats are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify the main areas of work on habitat management, such as the formation of grasslands, as well as ways to maintain forests in a state optimal for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened with extinction due to construction and development works that affect their habitation and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can be dangerous, as can fly adhesive tape, chemical processing of building materials, and hunting of domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, their night hunting habits are such that their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo-location technique to pinpoint obstacles in the way of flight.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bat populations very seriously.
The organization employs ten trained experts who regularly conduct surveys, on-site inspections, and sometimes rescue work.
The organization even created Scotland's first and only bat reserve at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of the ten species of Scottish bats.
Property manager David Thompson says the estate is the perfect territory for them.
“Here at Threave, a great place for bats,” he says.
“There are old buildings, a lot of old trees and all the elements of a good habitat.
But much about bats remains unknown, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
He recalls the importance of checking for the presence of bats before carrying out maintenance within private holdings, since the unintentional destruction of one nest can lead to the death of up to 400 females and young individuals, and possibly even to the destruction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected by law, their destruction, harassment or destruction of their habitats is illegal.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish bat conservation officer, is calling on the public for help.
She says, “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we just don’t know how many of their individual species live.”
