How a trade war with America could be good for Beijing
Experts believe the first salvos of the U.S.-China trade war have been deafening, and while the battle is far from over, a split between the countries could benefit Beijing in the long run.
Donald Trump, the U.S. president, issued the first warning earlier this year, taxing major Chinese exports, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation took place this week, when new tariffs affected $200 billion ($150 billion) worth of goods, effectively taxing half of all goods coming into the U.S. from China.
Beijing has retaliated each time, recently imposing tariffs on $60 billion worth of U.S. goods ranging from five to ten percent.
China has promised that retaliatory measures against the United States will be equivalent every time, and the world’s second largest economy is unlikely to begin to experience even the slightest difficulties in the near future.
To force Washington to back down is to yield to demands, but publicly ceding to the U.S. would be too shameful for Xi Jinping, China’s president.
Still, experts say if Beijing can play its cards right, U.S. trade war pressure could provide long-term support to China by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that an early political decision in Washington or Beijing could create conditions that would lead to an economic tailspin in any of these countries is actually far more dangerous than observers have previously acknowledged,” said Abigail Grace, a research fellow at the Center for New American Security, a think tank specializing in Asia.
Syrian Foreign Minister Says Syria 'Ready' for Refugee Return
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and is seeking help to rebuild the country, which has been devastated by a war lasting more than seven years.
