Red tide: the concentration of microorganisms decreased in Pinellas, Manati and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows an overall decrease in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, in areas of Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, abundant flowering is reported, which indicates a decrease in the concentration of microorganisms.
The Red Tide extends approximately 130 miles of coastline from the northern Pinellas to the southern Lee counties.
Spots can be observed about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but compared to last week, their number has decreased significantly.
The red tide is also observed in Pasco County.
Average concentrations in and around Pinellas County were reported last week, from low to high concentrations in the Hillsborough County coastal area, high concentrations in Manati and Sarasota counties and coastal areas, average concentrations in Charlotte County, high concentrations on the Lee County coast, and low concentrations in Collier County.
In Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties, there is still a chance of airway irritation.
In northwestern Florida, no such possibility was reported last week.
